## Tools are hands

An agent without tools can only talk. An agent with tools can inspect, edit, test, deploy, schedule, message, browse, and verify.

The point is not tool count. The point is correct routing and proof.

## Tool taxonomy

| Tool class | Use | Verification |
|---|---|---|
| File tools | read, search, write, patch local artifacts | Read back files or inspect diff. |
| Terminal | build, test, run commands, inspect system state | Exit code and relevant output. |
| Browser | interactive web work, visual QA, account/session workflows | Screenshot, DOM state, or live page proof. |
| Web search/extract | current external facts and source extraction | Source URL and extracted content. |
| Memory tools | retain and recall durable facts | Recall result and memory policy match. |
| Cron/background | recurring jobs and long-running processes | Job list/status/log/output. |
| Messaging | send reports or media to approved targets | Target, message ID, or platform delivery proof. |
| MCP | structured external systems: docs, tasks, notes, control planes | Tool call result against the live server. |

## Native toolset lifecycle

Use Hermes CLI to inspect and control native toolsets:

```bash
hermes tools
hermes tools list
hermes tools enable <toolset>
hermes tools disable <toolset>
```

Operational rules:

- enable the smallest toolset that can do the job;
- do not expose browser/account/social tools to profiles that do not need them;
- terminal/file tools require stronger verification discipline because they can modify local state;
- public messaging tools require approval gates before external send/share/post actions.

## MCP layer examples

Useful MCP servers:

- Context7 for current library docs;
- NotebookLM for source notebooks;
- Paperclip for company control state;
- Linear for issues/projects;
- Notion for docs/databases;
- Google Workspace for Gmail/Drive/Calendar/Docs/Sheets depending on setup.

## MCP lifecycle commands

Use Hermes MCP commands instead of treating MCP as a static config blob:

```bash
hermes mcp add <name> --url <remote-http-url>
hermes mcp add <name> --command <stdio-command>
hermes mcp list
hermes mcp status
hermes mcp login <name>
hermes mcp remove <name>
```

After adding a server, run a minimal read-only call through the exposed tool before claiming the integration works.

## Remote MCP OAuth pattern

Hosted MCP servers often require OAuth. Configure the server with OAuth auth and log in per Hermes profile:

```yaml
mcp_servers:
  notion:
    url: https://mcp.notion.com/mcp
    auth: oauth
  linear:
    url: https://mcp.linear.app/mcp
    auth: oauth
```

Then authenticate:

```bash
hermes mcp login notion
hermes mcp login linear
hermes mcp status
```

Important distinctions:

- MCP server configured ≠ MCP authenticated;
- OAuth login success ≠ workspace/page/project permission granted;
- tool appears in schema ≠ the account has access to the target resource;
- read access ≠ write/share/delete approval.

## Capability checks

Before saying a capability exists, verify it:

- list tool availability;
- run a small read-only call;
- check auth status where possible;
- inspect error messages;
- document fallback path.

Proof examples:

| Capability claim | Minimum proof |
|---|---|
| Tools are enabled | `hermes tools list` shows target toolset. |
| MCP is available | `hermes mcp status` plus one read-only tool result. |
| Notion works | Fetch one shared page/database. |
| Linear works | List or fetch one accessible issue/project. |
| Browser works | Open page and inspect snapshot/screenshot. |
| Google works | Read-only profile-specific Gmail/Drive/Calendar check. |

## Tool-grounded response rule

Map claim type to proof:

| Claim | Proof |
|---|---|
| file content | read file |
| system state | terminal command |
| current external fact | web search/extract |
| account state | platform-specific status or owner-state check |
| MCP integration | actual MCP call |
| source material | extract/read transcript/source |
| completion | fresh verification command |

## Cron and background tools

Cron is an operational tool, not just a reminder system.

Use it for:

- daily pulse;
- weekly stale-task audit;
- health checks;
- API/feed watchdogs;
- cost and usage alerts;
- memory/skill review queues.

Key concepts:

- `script`: collect data before the agent reasons;
- `no_agent`: deliver script stdout directly, stay silent on empty stdout;
- `deliver`: target platform/channel;
- `workdir`: project context;
- `context_from`: chain previous job output.

Cron jobs must be self-contained. Do not rely on the current chat context.

## Failure modes

Common operating risks:

- treating memory as current system state;
- trusting subagent reports without checking output;
- using browser metadata instead of source transcript;
- declaring account login from cookie file existence;
- saying deploy succeeded without fetching the public URL;
- adding tools without risk gates;
- `401` from remote MCP treated as server outage when OAuth is missing;
- OAuth success treated as API readiness;
- tool listed in schema treated as permission to write;
- gateway running treated as successful message delivery;
- cron created without a delivery target or self-contained prompt.

## Custom MCP server rule

Build a custom MCP server only when:

- the action repeats;
- the API is stable;
- auth can be handled safely;
- outputs can be structured;
- least privilege is possible.

Otherwise use CLI/script wrappers first.

## Approval boundary

Tool availability never grants action permission by itself.

Require explicit approval for:

- external sends, shares, invites, posts, replies, likes, follows;
- destructive operations;
- production deploy/restart/security changes;
- money, billing, wallet, subscription, or API-spend increases;
- credential recovery or permission changes;
- public docs publishing when private material could leak.
